<article>
    <h1>Phil Collins&#x2019; 1981 hit back on charts after vi&#xAD;ral video</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20200817/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-08-17"><time>2020-08-17</time></a>
        - <span>LIFE | TRENDING</span>
        - <span role="byline"></span>
    </section>

    <p>LOS AN­GE­LES • Phil Collins’ In The Air Tonight has made a huge come­back in the mu­sic charts nearly 40 years after its re­lease, thanks to a vi­ral video of two young Amer­i­can broth­ers re­act­ing to his 1981 hit.</p>
    <p>Twins Tim and Fred Wil­liams, 22, posted a video of them­selves lis­ten­ing to the Bri­tish singer’s de­but solo sin­gle for the first time on YouTube last month.</p>
    <p>They are seen nod­ding along to Collins’ track, when sud­denly they fall back in their chairs – j aws dropped – as the drum beats drop in the mid­dle of the song. “This is unique,” says one of the twins in the video. “I’ve never seen any­one drop a beat at the end of a song.”</p>
    <p>The video on the twins’ YouTube chan­nel, Twin­s­the­newTrend, has racked up more than five mil­lion views. Last Fri­day, In the Air Tonight was No. 2 on the United States’ iTunes charts, be­hind Dar­ius Rucker’s Beers And Sun­shine, ac­cord­ing to itopchart.com.</p>
    <p>The hit launched Collins’ solo ca­reer in 1981, after he left Bri­tish rock group Gen­e­sis as its front man and drum­mer.</p>
    <p>Collins, 69, has sold more than 100 mil­lion al­bums dur­ing his solo ca­reer and 150 mil­lion with Gen­e­sis.</p>

